The paper deals with representation languages for coalitional games, which is a key research area in algorithmic game theory (cs.GT). The problem of finding the optimal coalition structure in Weighted Graph Games (WGGs) involves partitioning agents in a graph, which is a combinatorial problem (cs.DS). The paper proposes algorithms for finding constant factor approximations for planar, minor-free and bounded degree graphs, which involves computational complexity and optimization (cs.AI). The problem also involves analyzing the structure of graphs, particularly planar graphs, which falls under computational geometry (cs.CG). Finally, the paper deals with cooperative games, which is a subfield of social choice theory and falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
